Clodio must be excluded was seen by Madvig, who says, ‘it is not only superfluous, but spoils the sense, the contrast being between the chieftain and one of his followers‚ so that the proper name cannot be added to ‘the general term’ [Op. Ac. i. 154]. He thought the words a gloss to duce. If duce however remains, apart from the evidence afforded by the confusion in the MSS„ the sense is strange. Clodius is said to have burnt the Curia, uno ex suis satell. duce. If we ask, whom the satelles led, the answer can only be, ‘ the ghost of Clodius.' The phrase is only applicable if he was dux to a crowd: cf. ᾗ 95 multitudinem, quae P. Clodio duce . . . imminebat. With the reading which I propose the antitheses are ille >< unus ex. s. sat„ vivus >< mortuo, mali nihil fecisset >< curiam incenderit. The emendation is accepted by Poynton. Col- son erroneously terms it the reading of H.

2. sanctitatis: ‘ morality ' : ‘sanctus as an epithet is especially used of states- men, who discharge the dictates of morality towards the state and society so far as it comes into contact with the state ' [Seyffem Lael. p. 28o].

amplitudinis: the senate being am- plissimus ordo, cf. ξ 4n.

3. consili. publici: cf. Cato M. 19 summum consilium of the senate: so Leg. Agr. ii. 88 si. . . publicum ex illa urbe consilium sustulissent, where it signifies the local senate of Capua. 1 cannot agree with Dr. Reid, who says that cons. publ. does not mean here ‘the senate‚’ bnt is used as sest. 43 sanguis nullo publico consilio profusus.

caput urbis : for the variant orbis see

§ 72 n. Possibly, however, orbis (terrae) should be read, cf. Fam. iii. 8. 4 in publico orbis terrae consilio, id est, in senatu, Phil. vii. 19 summo consilio orbis terrae.

aram . . . portum: cf. Verr. v. 126 hie portus, haec arx, haec ara sociorum, Caecin. 100 exsilium . . . est perfugium portusque supplici . . . confugiunt quasi ad aram, in exsilium.

4. uni: Rau objects to this that it would be invidious to speak of the Curia as the peculias possession of one privileged order. Cicero, however, uses the word without attaching special meaning to it, as yielding his favourite antithesis of unus and universus, e. g. Sest. 27, 33, 122, 128, &c- Cf. 5 34 n.

5. inflammari: cf. the line of Ennius haec omnia vidi inflammari Sest. 121. exscindi: I somewhat doubt the genuine· ness of this word: the corruption in H seems to point to its having originally been a supra-lineal addition.

fune-tari: sc. by the corpse of Clodius: cf. Rab. Perd. 11 funestari contionem contagione carnificis veto.

6. ab uno: Cicero here attributes the deed to Sextus alone, not as Asconius, to

*the multitude led by him. This is a

strong argument against the words Sex. Clodio duce supr.

7. ustor: a slave belonging to the libitinarius, ef. sordidus ustor, Lucan, viii. 738, semirasus u., Catull. lix. 5 [Wirz].

signifer: cs. Att. ii. 1. 7 te signifero ac principe, Plane. 74 causae nostrae duces et quasi signiferi, Ascon. 33 antesig- nanus servorum.
